ce:section.ce:para:
The effect of the pH on the lysine sensitivity was investigated (Fig. 5
                        ). The fluorescence intensity of the N-GQDs and N,S-GQDs changed significantly from pH 3.2 to pH 9.2 when lysine was added, respectively. The optimal pH value was found to be 6.2. With lower pH, more H+ attached to the surface of the quantum dots repulsing the protonated lysine. When the pH increased above 7.2, a large amount of OH− approached the positive lysine preventing it from reaching the quantum dots. Although the fluorescence intensities of the N-GQDs and N,S-GQDs decreased by approximately 11% and 20%, respectively, at the pH of 7.2, the two quantum dots still responded well to lysine. This suggests that the two nanosensors can be applied in biological imaging. The phenomenon agrees with the positive ɛ-amine of lysine interacting with the quantum dots. The course can be expected reversible. Fluorescent probes with reversible properties are very useful in practical applications. As shown in Fig. S11, the N-GQDs and N,S-GQDs can be reused as fluorescent probes at least ten times without apparent fluorescence intensity decline. A solution of N-GQDs with human serum at a concentration of 1.0 g/L and a separate solution of lysine in human serum with a concentration of 1.0 g/ L was prepared. As shown in Fig. 6
                        , an excellent linear relationship was observed between the relative fluorescence enhancement of the N-GQDs and the lysine concentration in the serum within the range of 0.049–0.206 mM. With the N,S-GQDs, a linear concentration of lysine between 0.015 and 0.202 mM was observed. In a previous study, the concentrations of lysine in serum was reported to be approximately 0.08 to 0.18 mM [46]. Therefore, the two doped graphene-based nanosensors can be fine-tuned to detect lysine in serum with good sensitivity.
